<catsoop-section>LEDs</catsoop-section>

An LED is a one-way part (it has direction).
- The long leg is usually the anode (+ side).
- The short leg is usually the cathode (– side).
- The flat side on the LED body usually marks the cathode.

Important:
An LED must have a resistor in series.

Mini build: light one LED (test circuit)
1. Power OFF.
2. Place 1 LED on the breadboard (legs in different rows).
3. Place 1 resistor (220–330 Ω).
4. Wire: +V rail → resistor → LED anode (long leg).
5. Wire: LED cathode (short leg) → GND rail.
6. Turn power ON. The LED should light.
7. Turn power OFF again before continuing.

If it does not light:
- Flip the LED (it may be backwards).
- Check that the resistor is actually in series (not accidentally on the same node).
- Check that rails are powered correctly.

